â€œI love bed rottingâ€ â€œmy room is a bit messy, itâ€™s such a depression room rn!â€  None of this is fun or quirky. Itâ€™s debilitating. And I know my room is disgusting and unhygienic but this is the reality of what depression can do to some people. iâ€™m not lazy and the mess does bother me greatly, but I physically am not able to do anything about it.  This is hard for me to post because iâ€™m so embarrassed about the state of my room and donâ€™t want anyone to see it and judge me. Most of my closest friends have never even seen my room, because this is the state itâ€™s in 98% of the time. But i want to be open and vulnerable on here to show people itâ€™s nothing to be ashamed about. Depression is an extremely painful sickness and even surviving through the day is a great battle, so if your room also looks like this or if youâ€™re beating yourself up for having a messy room, know that iâ€™m proud of you and you are doing the very best you can !  Iâ€™m also seeing allot of people refer to there room as a â€˜depressionâ€™ room as a way of using the word depression as an adjective. Depression is not an adjective. Itâ€™s an incredible difficult illness that many people d!â‚¬ from. It should not be used as a replacement for the word â€˜messyâ€™. If a few of your clothes are on your chair instead of in your closet or if you forgot to put away a cup; thatâ€™s something very different from a â€˜depression roomâ€™. People who suffer from depression find even getting up to use the toilet too much sometimes; our room reflects how our depression manifests itself (and itâ€™s not pretty)  I for example how molding food in my room, countless empty bottles and plates, used bandages that have never been thrown away and even mice and other insects. I cannot see my floor. Iâ€™m constantly breaking my neck trying to get to my bed or out of my room. Iâ€™ve broken countless things by accidently having stepped on them. I have no idea where most of my clothes are or if any of it is even clean. Iâ€™ve lost many important things because of the state of my room. Iâ€™m constantly late (which i am known for among my friends) but what they donâ€™t know is itâ€™s because i canâ€™t find anything, which in turn stresses me out till the point of a panic attack, but iâ€™m always too embarrassed to tell them that.  One thing that also upsets me is how much â€˜bed rottingâ€™ has become a trend. Taking a nap or laying in a little longer, is not â€˜rottingâ€™, thatâ€™s just resting. There have been a few times in my life where is spent weeks in my bed, and the only time I ever got up was to go to the toilet (and usually only after many hours of trying to ignore the fact that i have to pee because I didnâ€™t want get up). One of the worst depressions in my life I spent 3 whole months in bed. And the entire time i did this, my bed clothes where not changed once. My pillow soaked up all the dirt of my unwashed hair and in turn made my skin horrible. In those 3 months i also gained an immense amount of weight because i was not moving. Other times I didnâ€™t eat at all because I was too sucked into my â€˜bed rottingâ€™ i couldnâ€™t even be bothered to make food.  None of this should be a â€˜trendâ€™, itâ€™s not in anyway quirky or funny. Itâ€™s life altering and so incredibly difficult to go through and live with.
